tweet: For #Bitcoin, a close below 53,000 today, from a price structure, sets up that it has an intermediate peak in place.  This means it needs a few weeks to months to catch its breath.  A good time to add to long-term holdings.  A bad time to be over-leveraged.

name: John F. Carter
tweet: @BdtBoston In general I have found my best entries are "at" the 21.  ie buy pullbacks in an uptrend to that level and sell rallies in downtrends to that level.  At the extremes, take profits.  Then wait for the next retracement.

name: John F. Carter
tweet: Tricky spot here in $NQ.  Shorts are covered, but the long side looks sus (as my kids would say).  Remember in trading there are three positions: Long, short, or cash.  Cash is a mental vacation that brings back clarity.

name: John F. Carter
tweet: @BdtBoston Short the rallies back to the 21 then when it rolls over and pukes and falls away from the 21 and reaches extensions, cover shorts.  This is an area to cover shorts and wait for a new, clean entry.

name: John F. Carter
tweet: @Boots3452 You can do both.  On a daily chart I'll end up holding the trade for a few days to a few weeks.  On a 30M chart it is either day trade or it lasts a day or two as the price structure plays out.  i.e.,. a daily setup might be good for 10 points while a 30m setup good for 2.

name: John F. Carter
tweet: @Boots3452 I tend to focus on daily charts and then use 30-minute charts for shorter-term trades.

name: John F. Carter
tweet: @Peter12890842 I look to the indexes first as they tend to move most of the stocks with them, but there will always be exceptions.  While I like the short side of $QQQ I like the long side of $DKNG

name: John F. Carter
tweet: @BackJackBlack @ChartingOptions I generally exit 2 ATR from the 21 EMA.  You can see the 2 ATR levels by plotting Keltner Channels with a 21 EMA, and input 2 for the ATR.  (ATR = Average True Range).  I just use the default 14 periods for the ATR.
